<!-- ====== FAQ ====== -->
<section class="cc-faq">
  <div class="cc-faq__container">
    <h2 class="cc-faq__heading">Common questions about {{ condition_name | downcase }}</h2>

    {% if page.handle == 'fungal-acne' %}
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>How is fungal acne different from regular acne? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Fungal acne is a yeast infection of the hair follicle. Regular acne is driven by sebum, dead skin, and bacteria. Fungal acne shows as small, uniform, often itchy bumps that don't respond to typical acne treatments.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Why do my acne products make it worse? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Most acne products and moisturizers contain fatty acids and oils that <em>Malassezia</em> feeds on (the C11 to C24 range). Apply them to colonized skin and the yeast has more fuel.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Will it come back after treatment? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Often, yes. <em>Malassezia</em> is a normal part of human skin, so the goal is balance, not eradication. The recurring plans cover ongoing maintenance so you stay clear after the first round.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>What does the prescription typically cover? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>If your provider decides a prescription is the right call, that typically means a topical antifungal (e.g., ketoconazole) applied as a short-contact wash or cream on affected areas.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Do I need a video call or in-person visit? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>The standard consultation is fully async. You submit photos and a written intake; a clinician reviews and replies within 48 hours. Live video visits are an optional add-on for recurring plans.</p></div>
      </details>
    {% endif %}

    {% if page.handle == 'seb-derm-dandruff' %}
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Is dandruff the same thing as seborrheic dermatitis? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>They're on the same spectrum. Dandruff is essentially scalp seb derm with less inflammation. Both come from <em>Malassezia</em> overgrowth and respond to the same treatment approach.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Why didn't anti-dandruff shampoo work for me? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>OTC anti-dandruff shampoos can help mild cases, but stronger flares, facial seb derm, and chronic cases usually need prescription-strength antifungals plus a maintenance routine your clinician designs.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Can stress trigger flares? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Yes. Stress, weather changes, lack of sleep, and certain hair products are common triggers. Your treatment plan covers what to do when triggers hit so flares don't escalate.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Is it contagious? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>No. <em>Malassezia</em> lives on almost every adult's skin. Seb derm and dandruff happen when the yeast overgrows in your specific environment, not because you caught it from someone.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>What does the prescription typically cover? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>If your provider decides a prescription is the right call, that typically means a topical antifungal (e.g., ketoconazole) for the affected zones, applied for a few weeks initially and then on a maintenance cadence.</p></div>
      </details>
    {% endif %}

    {% if page.handle == 'tinea-versicolor' %}
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>How long until the patches even out? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>The yeast itself is usually treated in 2 to 4 weeks. The pigment evens out over the weeks following treatment as your skin's pigment production recovers. It's normal for the patches to be visible for a while after the active infection is cleared.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Why does it keep coming back every summer? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Heat and humidity are the perfect environment for <em>Malassezia</em> to overgrow. Tinea versicolor relapses seasonally for many people. The recurring plans cover prevention so you don't start from scratch each year.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Is it dangerous or contagious? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Not dangerous to your overall health and not contagious. <em>Malassezia</em> lives on nearly all human skin; the condition is local overgrowth in your specific environment, not a transmission.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>What does the prescription typically cover? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>If your provider decides a prescription is the right call, that typically means a topical antifungal (e.g., ketoconazole) applied for a couple of weeks. Most cases clear with a single short course.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="cc-faq__item">
        <summary>Can sun exposure make it worse? <svg class="cc-faq__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></summary>
        <div class="cc-faq__answer"><p>Sun makes the patches more visible, since the affected areas can't tan with the rest of your skin. The condition itself is mostly driven by heat, humidity, and oil production, not sunlight directly.</p></div>
      </details>
    {% endif %}
  </div>
</section>

